/**
 * Process items by converting each to uppercase.
 * Known issue: users report the last item is never processed.
 */
export function processItems(items: string[]): string[] {
  const results: string[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < items.length - 1; i++) {
    results.push(items[i].toUpperCase());
  }
  return results;
}
```

**Lines 5-11** contain the function.

### 2. The Exact Bug

**Bug Location:** Line 7 — the loop condition

**The Problem:** 
```typescript
for (let i = 0; i < items.length - 1; i++)
```

This condition uses `items.length - 1` as the upper bound, which means the loop stops **before** reaching the last item. The loop variable `i` will iterate from `0` to `items.length - 2`, effectively skipping the element at index `items.length - 1` (the last item).

**Why it happens:** The condition `i < items.length - 1` is equivalent to `i < items.length - 1`, so when `i` equals `items.length - 2`, the loop continues. When `i` becomes `items.length - 1`, the condition `items.length - 1 < items.length - 1` evaluates to `false`, and the loop terminates without processing the last element.

**The Fix:**
Change line 7 from:
```typescript
for (let i = 0; i < items.length - 1; i++)
```

To:
```typescript
for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++)
```

This makes the loop iterate through all indices from `0` to `items.length - 1` (inclusive), ensuring the last item is processed.

